item.title: The Christian refugees who can never return to Mosul
item.description: Anne Danyale can never go back to Mosul.

item.title: Military strategies in the fight for Mosul
item.description: The military operation to retake Mosul from ISIS continues, but what are the strategies used on both sides? CNN's Fred Pleitgen breaks it down.

item.title: Mosul offensive enters second week: All you need to know
item.description: The terrifying scene has played out time and again. Amid a chaotic battlefield, an unknown vehicle barrels across the Nineveh plains, kicking up clouds of dust in its wake. It's speeding toward Iraqi or Kurdish Peshmerga front lines with a cargo of high explosives. Soldiers fire rockets and missiles in a frantic effort to destroy the vehicle before it kills them. Sometimes they find their target; sometimes not.

item.title: Defusing ISIS bombs with bare hands and little else
item.description: Along a dusty village track just 20 kilometers (12 miles) from Mosul, a Peshmerga pick up truck leads us to a small house. We drive slowly, and in single file. There are hidden dangers all around.

item.title: Demolition underway of Calais 'Jungle' camp
item.description: A team of workers in France began the long-awaited demolition of the "Jungle" migrant camp on Tuesday, pulling down tents, shacks and other makeshift shelters that thousands have called home over the past two years.

item.title: Vatican: No scattering of cremated remains
item.description: The Vatican announced Tuesday that Catholics may be cremated but may not have their ashes scattered at sea or kept in urns at home.

item.title: BA flight diverted after cabin crew became ill
item.description: A British Airways flight from San Francisco to London was diverted to Vancouver Tuesday morning after members of the cabin crew became ill, the airline said.

item.title: How Asia's changing skylines inspire the world
item.description: When it comes to architectural innovation, some of the most significant changes to urban skylines over the past half-century have occurred in Asia.

item.title: At least 4 dead in Queensland theme park incident
item.description: Four adults have been killed after an incident at a theme park on Tuesday in Queensland, Australia, Queensland Police said in a statement.

item.title: 5 years later: Libyans recall the moment of Gadhafi's death
item.description: Five years on from the inglorious end to Gadhafi's life, ordinary Libyans reveal their memories of the moment they heard the dictator had died and share their hopes for the future of their homeland.

item.title: Intimate ballet portraits showcase the 'Art of Movement'
item.description: Deborah Ory discovered dance photography when she could no longer be a dancer herself.

item.title: 1st woman to climb Everest dies
item.description: Junko Tabei, the first woman to climb the world's highest peak, has died at age 77, according to Japanese media reports.

item.title: Guard killed; 174 inmates escape
item.description: A manhunt is underway after 174 inmates escaped from a prison in Haiti following a riot during which one guard was killed, authorities said.

item.title: Hostages held nearly 5 years freed
item.description: Somali pirates have released 26 hostages after nearly five years in captivity, according to an organization involved in mediation efforts.

item.title: One man's flight to freedom in a hay stack
item.description: Sunday marks the 60th anniversary of the ill-fated revolution, one man remembers escaping the violence that would leave 2,500 Hungarians dead and so many more displaced.

item.title: Zombies walk Mexico City streets
item.description: Enthusiasts take part in a zombie walk in Mexico City.

item.title: Millions of IP addresses used in cyberattack
CNN set to announce top 10 Heroes for 2016
item.description: CNN's Anderson Cooper will reveal which charitable champs will be among this year's Top 10 CNN Heroes on Wednesday during the 8 a.m. ET hour of "New Day."

item.title: Opium fuels stalemate in America's longest war
item.description: America's longest war received only a passing mention during the three debates between American presidential nominees Donald Trump and Hillary Clinton.

item.title: Tom Hayden never lost passion for social justice
item.description: The death of Tom Hayden -- the iconic anti-war and civil rights activist, who was perhaps the most recognizable face of the New Left in the 1960s -- represents a great loss to all who believe in social justice.

item.title: Russian hack is just a warning sign
item.description: The Russian hack is a warning sign of things to come, writes Amy Zegart. The US had better be prepared

item.title: Obamacare premiums to soar 22%
item.description: Obamacare premiums are set to skyrocket an average of 22% for the benchmark silver plan in 2017, according to a government report released Monday.

item.title: Brexit Britain: Microsoft hikes prices by 22%
item.description: Microsoft products are about to get a whole lot more expensive for U.K. buyers.

item.title: EU-Canada trade deal on life support
item.description: Last-minute negotiations to salvage the European Union's signature free trade agreement have been dealt a major blow by a rogue regional government in Belgium.

item.title: A new perspective of our planet
item.description: On Christmas Eve in 1968, Apollo 8 made the first manned mission to the moon. Live broadcasting from the spacecraft was the three-man crew of Frank Borman, Jim Lovell and William Anders, and it was on that day that their journey led them to an unexpected sight.

item.title: Galaxy count just increased 10x
item.description: Turns out we were wrong; there aren't 200 billion galaxies in the universe.

item.title: Study: Mars mission astronauts could experience brain damage
item.description: Astronauts on a mission to Mars will be expected to rely on their memory, multitasking and decision-making skills to handle the first manned expedition beyond the moon. But the harmful radiation from galactic cosmic rays throughout their journey could cause them to experience cognitive impairment in these key areas, as well as increased depression and anxiety, according to a new study.

item.title: New Mars probe searches for life
item.description: A new phase in the continuing search for life on Mars begins this month -- adding to a fleet of spacecraft probing the Red Planet.

item.title: What it would take to explore deep space
item.description: Imagine something so distant that with our current technology it would take 2,400 generations to reach there -- and that's just our nearest star.
